#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:8
msgid "Spack for Homebrew/Conda Users"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:10
msgid ""
"Spack is an incredibly powerful package manager, designed for supercomputers "
"where users have diverse installation needs. But Spack can also be used to "
"handle simple single-user installations on your laptop. Most macOS users are "
"already familiar with package managers like Homebrew and Conda, where all "
"installed packages are symlinked to a single central location like ``/usr/"
"local``. In this section, we will show you how to emulate the behavior of "
"Homebrew/Conda using :ref:`environments`!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:20
msgid "Setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:22
msgid ""
"First, let's create a new environment. We'll assume that Spack is already "
"set up correctly, and that you've already sourced the setup script for your "
"shell. To create a new environment, simply run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:26
msgid "$ spack env create myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:30
msgid ""
"Here, *myenv* can be anything you want to name your environment. Next, we "
"can add a list of packages we would like to install into our environment. "
"Let's say we want a newer version of Bash than the one that comes with "
"macOS, and we want a few Python libraries. We can run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:35
msgid "$ spack -e myenv add bash@5 python py-numpy py-scipy py-matplotlib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:39
msgid ""
"Each package can be listed on a separate line, or combined into a single "
"line like we did above. Notice that we're explicitly asking for Bash 5 here. "
"You can use any spec you would normally use on the command line with other "
"Spack commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:43
msgid "Next, we want to manually configure a couple of things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:45
msgid "$ spack -e myenv config edit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:49
msgid ""
"# This is a Spack Environment file.\n"
"#\n"
"# It describes a set of packages to be installed, along with\n"
"# configuration settings.\n"
"spack:\n"
"  # add package specs to the `specs` list\n"
"  specs: [bash@5, python, py-numpy, py-scipy, py-matplotlib]\n"
"  view: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:60
msgid ""
"You can see the packages we added earlier in the ``specs:`` section. If you "
"ever want to add more packages, you can either use ``spack add`` or manually "
"edit this file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:64
msgid ""
"We also need to change the ``concretizer:unify`` option. By default, Spack "
"concretizes each spec *separately*, allowing multiple versions of the same "
"package to coexist. Since we want a single consistent environment, we want "
"to concretize all of the specs *together*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:69
msgid "Here is what your ``spack.yaml`` looks like with this new setting:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:71
msgid ""
"# This is a Spack Environment file.\n"
"#\n"
"# It describes a set of packages to be installed, along with\n"
"# configuration settings.\n"
"spack:\n"
"  # add package specs to the `specs` list\n"
"  specs: [bash@5, python, py-numpy, py-scipy, py-matplotlib]\n"
"  view: true\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:86
msgid "Symlink location"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:88
msgid ""
"Spack symlinks all installations to ``/Users/me/spack/var/spack/environments/"
"myenv/.spack-env/view``, which is the default when ``view: true``. You can "
"actually change this to any directory you want. For example, Homebrew uses "
"``/usr/local``, while Conda uses ``/Users/me/anaconda``. In order to access "
"files in these locations, you need to update ``PATH`` and other environment "
"variables to point to them. Activating the Spack environment does this "
"automatically, but you can also manually set them in your ``.bashrc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:98
msgid "There are several reasons why you shouldn't use ``/usr/local``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:100
msgid ""
"If you are on macOS 10.11+ (El Capitan and newer), Apple makes it hard for "
"you. You may notice permissions issues on ``/usr/local`` due to their "
"`System Integrity Protection <https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT204899>`_. "
"By default, users don't have permissions to install anything in ``/usr/"
"local``, and you can't even change this using ``sudo chown`` or ``sudo "
"chmod``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:105
msgid ""
"Other package managers like Homebrew will try to install things to the same "
"directory. If you plan on using Homebrew in conjunction with Spack, don't "
"symlink things to ``/usr/local``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:108
msgid ""
"If you are on a shared workstation, or don't have sudo privileges, you can't "
"do this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:111
msgid ""
"If you still want to do this anyway, there are several ways around SIP. You "
"could disable SIP by booting into recovery mode and running ``csrutil "
"disable``, but this is not recommended, as it can open up your OS to "
"security vulnerabilities. Another technique is to run ``spack concretize`` "
"and ``spack install`` using ``sudo``. This is also not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:117
msgid ""
"The safest way I've found is to create your installation directories using "
"sudo, then change ownership back to the user like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:120
msgid ""
"for directory in .spack bin contrib include lib man share\n"
"do\n"
"    sudo mkdir -p /usr/local/$directory\n"
"    sudo chown $(id -un):$(id -gn) /usr/local/$directory\n"
"done"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:128
msgid ""
"Depending on the packages you install in your environment, the exact list of "
"directories you need to create may vary. You may also find some packages "
"like Java libraries that install a single file to the installation prefix "
"instead of in a subdirectory. In this case, the action is the same, just "
"replace ``mkdir -p`` with ``touch`` in the for-loop above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:134
msgid "But again, it's safer just to use the default symlink location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:139
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:141
msgid "To actually concretize the environment, run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:143
msgid "$ spack -e myenv concretize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:147
msgid ""
"This will tell you which if any packages are already installed, and alert "
"you to any conflicting specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:150
msgid ""
"To actually install these packages and symlink them to your ``view:`` "
"directory, simply run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:153
msgid ""
"$ spack -e myenv install\n"
"$ spack env activate myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:158
msgid ""
"Now, when you type ``which python3``, it should find the one you just "
"installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:160
msgid ""
"In order to change the default shell to our newer Bash installation, we "
"first need to add it to this list of acceptable shells. Run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:163
msgid "$ sudo vim /etc/shells"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:167
msgid "and add the absolute path to your bash executable. Then run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:169
msgid "$ chsh -s /path/to/bash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:173
msgid ""
"Now, when you log out and log back in, ``echo $SHELL`` should point to the "
"newer version of Bash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:178
msgid "Updating Installed Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:180
msgid ""
"Let's say you upgraded to a new version of macOS, or a new version of Python "
"was released, and you want to rebuild your entire software stack. To do "
"this, simply run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:184
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack concretize --fresh --force\n"
"$ spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:190
msgid ""
"The ``--fresh`` flag tells Spack to use the latest version of every package "
"where possible instead of trying to optimize for reuse of existing installed "
"packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:194
msgid ""
"The ``--force`` flag in addition tells Spack to overwrite its previous "
"concretization decisions, allowing you to choose a new version of Python. If "
"any of the new packages like Bash are already installed, ``spack install`` "
"won't re-install them, it will keep the symlinks in place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:201
msgid "Updating & Cleaning Up Old Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:203
msgid ""
"If you're looking to mimic the behavior of Homebrew, you may also want to "
"clean up out-of-date packages from your environment after an upgrade. To "
"upgrade your entire software stack within an environment and clean up old "
"package versions, simply run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:208
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack mark -i --all\n"
"$ spack concretize --fresh --force\n"
"$ spack install\n"
"$ spack gc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:216
msgid ""
"Running ``spack mark -i --all`` tells Spack to mark all of the existing "
"packages within an environment as \"implicitly\" installed. This tells "
"spack's garbage collection system that these packages should be cleaned up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:220
msgid ""
"Don't worry however, this will not remove your entire environment. Running "
"``spack install`` will reexamine your spack environment after a fresh "
"concretization and will re-mark any packages that should remain installed as "
"\"explicitly\" installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:225
msgid ""
"**Note:** if you use multiple spack environments you should re-run ``spack "
"install`` in each of your environments prior to running ``spack gc`` to "
"prevent spack from uninstalling any shared packages that are no longer "
"required by the environment you just upgraded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:232
msgid "Uninstallation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:234
msgid ""
"If you decide that Spack isn't right for you, uninstallation is simple. Just "
"run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:237
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack uninstall --all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../replace_conda_homebrew.rst:242
msgid ""
"This will uninstall all packages in your environment and remove the symlinks."
msgstr ""
